# cursorProxy Core Context

- `cursorProxy` is an edge-compatible multi-provider AI proxy for DeepSeek, Kimi, MiniMax, Xiaomi MiMo, GLM / ZHIPU AI, and Azure Foundry.
- `api/proxy.js` is the main entrypoint and holds the provider orchestration.
- `lib/models.js` handles model parsing, public/private model IDs, and provider routing.
- Azure adapters live in `lib/azure-openai.js` and `lib/azure-anthropic.js`.
- Kimi K2.x request sanitization lives in `lib/kimi.js` (`sanitizeKimiBody`); default Kimi model is `kimi-k2.7-code`.
- GLM request sanitization lives in `lib/glm.js` (`sanitizeGlmBody`); default GLM model is `glm-5.2`, default upstream is `https://open.bigmodel.cn/api/coding/paas/v4`, and global Z.AI uses `UPSTREAM_GLM=https://api.z.ai/api/coding/paas/v4`. GLM-5.2+ supports `reasoning_effort` (default `max`), overridable via the `GLM_REASONING_EFFORT` env var (precedence: env > client > default `max`); older GLM models have it stripped automatically.
- Reasoning and cache helpers live in `lib/reasoning.js`, `lib/cache.js`, and `lib/kv.js`.
- `api/proxy.js` and all `lib/*.js` files are shared edge-safe modules. Do not introduce `node:*` imports or `ioredis` there.
- `server.js` is the Docker-only wrapper around the shared proxy logic.
- `vercel.json` and `cloud-functions/` provide platform routing entrypoints.
- `cliProxy` at `/home/opc/cliProxy` is the sibling reference implementation for EdgeOne Pages deployment (see `.cursor/rules/edgeone-deployment.mdc`).
- Manual verification prompts live under `.cursor/test-cases/`.
- `wiki/` is a separate git clone for the GitHub wiki. Do not commit wiki changes in the main repo.
- For every new feature, provider, behavior change, env var, deployment change, or operator-facing fix, explicitly evaluate whether the GitHub wiki needs updating. If it does, update `wiki/` in the same work so docs ship with the code change; if it does not, be ready to state why.
- Keep `README.md` minimal and quick-start focused. Put optional configuration, provider-specific details, troubleshooting, tuning knobs, and long explanations in the wiki, then link from the README instead of expanding it.
- **Release process — THREE STEPS, two review gates, never auto-advance past a pause**:

  - **Step 1 (default — do proactively): local edits + commit.** Make edits, write tests, update wiki and rules, then `git commit` to the local branch (main repo and `wiki/` as appropriate). Do NOT `git push`, do NOT tag, do NOT `gh release create`. **PAUSE here and wait.** A separate review tool runs against the local commit.

  - **Step 2 (only after review sign-off): push the branch.** On explicit confirmation that review passed (e.g. "push", "looks good", "go ahead", "GA", or review feedback that has been addressed with a new Step 1 commit), `git push origin <branch>` (main repo) and `git push origin master` inside `wiki/`. Branch pushes trigger Vercel/EdgeOne/Docker auto-redeploy. Do NOT tag, do NOT `gh release create`. **PAUSE here and wait** if not also proceeding to Step 3.

  - **Step 3 (ONLY on the literal command "GA"): tag and release.** Treat anything that is not the exact word "GA" (review feedback, "go ahead", "push and release", "next step", "deploy", silence, etc.) as Step 1 or Step 2 work — never as Step 3. Only an explicit "GA" from the user triggers Step 3. On "GA", run the full sequence in one turn:
    1. Find the previous tag: `git tag --sort=-v:refname | head -5`.
    2. Determine the bump from `code-conventions.mdc` (patch = fixes/docs; minor = new provider or operator-facing feature; major = breaking).
    3. Confirm the target commit is already pushed (Step 2 handles this; if not, push now).
    4. Create the annotated tag with NO description body, using the commit's date as tagger date so tags sort chronologically on GitHub:
       `GIT_COMMITTER_DATE="<commit-date>" git tag -a vX.Y.Z <commit> -m "vX.Y.Z"`.
    5. Push the tag: `git push origin vX.Y.Z`.
    6. Create the GitHub release with full changelog comparing against the previous tag:
       `gh release create vX.Y.Z --notes "..."` (notes via heredoc).

  Tags must never carry descriptions; descriptions belong only on GitHub Releases. Never assume advancement from silence or from any phrase that isn't the explicit trigger for the next step.
